<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-646-713  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 646 713.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Nov 22 1990 v16 n24 p18(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Siemens Nixdorf looks for stronger identity. (company profile)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Frangini, Monica.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Siemens Nixdorf, formed in Oct 1990 by a merger between NixdorfComputer AG and Information Technology Group of Siemens AG, is aCanadian company that is part of a worldwide organization, SiemensNixdorf Information Systems AG, which claims to be the eighthlargest data processing company in the world with 50,000 employeesand 110,000 customers.andP;  Siemens Nixdorf sees itself as a Canadiancompany: it does not want to be seen as a European companyoperating in Canada.andP;  According to Frank Sagebiel, president andCEO at Siemens Nixdorf, the merger of the companies was perfect tocreate a European force with an impact in North America.andP;  Sagebielsays his company will address the systems integration area ofretail and point-of-sale systems, as well as point of servicessystems and imaging.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Siemens Nixdorf Information Systems Ltd. (Marketing).andO;Topic:     ImageComputer IndustryMergerForecastingCanadaCompany Profile.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Siemens Nixdorf looks for stronger identityandM;Newly-formed Siemens Nixdorf Information Systems Ltd. of Toronto will not letthe European reputation that accompanies its name stand in its way ofbecoming a truly Canadian corporation.andM;&quot;We very strongly wear a Canadian hat,&quot; said Frank Sagebiel, president andchief executive officer of Siemens Nixdorf.andP;  &quot;We don't want to appear in themarket as a European firm or a German firm ...andP;  It's our job to address theneeds of the Canadian market.&quot;andM;Siemens Nixdorf was formed last month as a result of the merger betweenEuropean computer companies, Nixdorf Computer AG and the data and InformationTechnology Group of Siemens AG.andM;The Canadian company is part of a new worldwide organization, Siemens NixdorfInformation Systems AG, which, according to the company, will be the eighthlargest data processing company in the world with over 50,000 employees andmore than 110,000 customers.andM;Sagebiel said the merger of the two companies was a perfect fit to create aEuropean force with a strong impact in North America.andM;&quot;Nixdorf is very strong on the market side and applications side of computertechnology.andP;  Also it has a very strong national presence,&quot; said Sagebiel whowas president of Nixdorf Computer Canada before the merger.andM;He added that Siemens' strengths are its information technology capabilities.andM;Siemens AG, headquartered in West Germany, is one of the world's largestmultinational corporations with sales over $47 billion.andM;There will be two areas that Siemens Nixdorf will be addressing in Canada,commented Sagebiel.andP;  &quot;One area is the systems integration where we providesolutions to our customers ...andP;  and the other is in the upper side which willinclude PCs, Unix systems, networks and laser printers.&quot;andM;Sagebiel said he especially sees the company as a very strong provider ofsolutions in the systems integration area of retail and point-of-salesystems, as well as point of services systems and imaging.andM;Siemens Nixdorf's largest contract to date has been with Canada Post Corp. tosupply retail point-of-service systems for the automation of postal countersacross Canada.andP;  &quot;This is a tremendous contract,&quot; said Sagebiel.andM;He added that over a five-year period a large number of postal outlets are tobe equipped with point-of-service terminals, specialized retail printers,weigh scales and bar code scanners.andO;</TEXT></DOC>